doc.previous: The first prototype made its maiden flight from Zhukovsky Airfield on 29 March 1990.[13] Development was slowed by technical problems (including delays with the TV7-117 engines), and by organisational and financial problems associated with the Break-up of the Soviet Union, with the Il-114 to be built at the Tashkent Aviation Production Association in soon to be independent Uzbekistan. The second prototype did not fly until 24 December 1991. This second prototype crashed, killing seven of nine people aboard, on 5 July 1993, causing the Russian government to withdraw funding from the Il-114, although the OKB continued development with its own money.[14][15] The Il-114 finally received airworthiness certification on 26 April 1997.[16]
